<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="holotype">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">China. Yunnan Province: Puer, Jingdong County, Wuliangshan National Nature Reserve, on fallen branch of angiosperm, 5 October 2017, CLZhao 4167 (SWFC).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
The epithet 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">wuliangshanensis</emphasis>
(Lat.): refers to the locality (Wuliangshan) of the type specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="basidiomata">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Basidiomata.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Annual, resupinate, subcoriaceous when fresh, becoming coriaceous upon drying, up to 15 cm long and 5 cm wide, 50-150 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
thick. Hymenial surface smooth to more or less tuberculate, white to cream when fresh, turning cream to buff upon drying. Margin narrow, concolorous with hymenial surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="hyphal system">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Hyphal system.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Monomitic; generative hyphae with clamp connections, hyaline, thick-walled, branched, 2-3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in diameter, IKI-, cyanophilous; tissues unchanged in KOH. Numerous crystals present among hyphae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="hymenium">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Hymenium.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Two kinds of cystidia: 1) capitate, hyaline, thin-walled, 22-37 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
; 2) tapering, hyaline, thin-walled, 21-35 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-6.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
; fusoid cystidioles present, hyaline, thin-walled, 16-21 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. Basidia clavate, hyaline, thin-walled, with four sterigmata and a basal clamp connection, 12-20 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-4.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="spores">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Spores.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Basidiospores ellipsoid, hyaline, slightly thick-walled, smooth, IKI-, cyanophilous, guttulate, (3.3-)3.5-5.3(-5.5) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.8-4(-4.2) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, L = 4.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, W = 3.56 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, Q = 1.22-1.31 (n = 120/4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Ecology and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Lignicolous, causing a white rot. China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
